nstrumentation**\\n\\nI'm considering whether our direct invocation of `class$` might be synthetic, and if the instrumentation properly covers that. It feels like it should! I’m thinking about creating a stronger test to invoke the Groovy enum helper `next` and `previous` after clearing synthetic cached class fields. If `class$` was cached, then `Class.forName` wouldn’t be called. \\n\\nIt seems that the direct `class$` always calls `Class.forName`, but I'm puzzled about whether MethodHandles invoke it correctly, especially with the signature. I wonder if the method might be package-private and what that means for our tests.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering a testing approach**\\n\\nI’m thinking about whether it would be beneficial to compile small Groovy code, but maybe that's not necessary. What I really need to do is write a test that triggers from a public API while also directly calling `class$` with all relevant class names. \\n\\nI might create a direct public test that forms parameters with URL encoding enabled for calls like `encode(BODY)` and handles path parameters with spaces. It could be great to use a local server to avoid any network issues!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_6zwBzBUzgQ3YwUyaLVXbC8cx|fc_0d15c043e38c7ba5016a00b2480498819f971d0ec99aec9a32", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "grep -R \"class URIBuilder\\|static.*encode\" -n /home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge8/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/source_context/io.rest-assured/rest-assured/5.5.0/main/extracted | head -40"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 852, "output": 956, "cacheRead": 28672, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 30480, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778430521125, "responseId": "resp_0d15c043e38c7ba5016a00b239d884819f809d2fdce5b61bca"}}
